Hi @xponentcrisis [τ, τ] Tensorplex, Thanks for finding our subnet interesting 🙂 
1) We are currently defining the search space in a config file inside the Orchestrator code. The search space defines the extent of the search, including parameters such as the number of layers, their depth, epochs, genetic algorithm population size, number of nodes, and so on. These numbers determine how long the experiment will take to complete. In the final product, when the front end is ready, the user will define these numbers, and we will estimate a charge based on the search space size.

2) We are in the very early stages and are trying to ensure we can run many experiments on public datasets without problems and without the influence of bad miners affecting the optimizer. We want to avoid providing incorrect results to a customer who pays for the service.

3) Yes, we are writing a short paper to publish at https://cvpr-nas.com, and the deadline is the 25th. I will be contacting the competition organizers to see if they will accept our results if we run the experiments in the subnet and submit the results or give them API access to the subnet.

4) We currently have two ML engineers on the technical side. The Subvortex team from Subnet 7, which is also our co-founder, will step in with marketing. I am planning to hire more team members to design the front end as soon as we reach a stable state in running many experiments on different datasets.

5) We are looking into recent publications for proof of learning to avoid this extra work by miners. The number of models that need to be validated in every generation is significant, and current proof of learning  algorithms seem to be computationally intensive. We also recently started to tap into miners' GPU utilization and power consumption data and have found some interesting correlations between dishonest mining behavior and hardware behavior.
